.TH POP3D 8 "February 2024" "pop3d" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
pop3d \- POP3 mail server
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pop3d
.RB [ \-c \fIfile\fP ]
.RB [ \-d ]
.RB [ \-g ]
.RB [ \-h ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B pop3d
is a POP3 mail server supporting both plaintext and SSL/TLS connections.
It uses PAM or shadow password authentication and stores mail in maildir format.
.PP
The server listens on two ports:
.IP \(bu 2
Port 110 \- POP3 with optional STARTTLS
.IP \(bu 2
Port 995 \- POP3S (SSL/TLS)
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-c \ file
Use the specified configuration file instead of the default
.IR /etc/pop3d.conf .
.TP
.B \-d
Run in the foreground (do not daemonize). Useful for debugging.
.TP
.B \-g
Generate a self-signed SSL certificate and exit.
.TP
.B \-h
Display usage information and exit.
.SH CONFIGURATION
The configuration file uses a simple key=value format.
See
.IR pop3d.conf (5)
for details.
.SS Authentication
.B pop3d
supports two authentication methods:
.IP 1. 3
PAM (preferred) - Uses the system PAM configuration
.IP 2. 3
Shadow passwords - Direct /etc/shadow access
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/pop3d.conf
Default configuration file
.TP
.I /etc/pam.d/pop3d
PAM configuration file
.TP
.I /etc/ssl/certs/pop3d.crt
Default SSL certificate
.TP
.I /etc/ssl/private/pop3d.key
Default SSL private key
.TP
.I /var/mail
Default mail storage directory
.SH EXAMPLES
Start the server:
.PP
.nf
.RS
sudo systemctl start pop3d
.RE
.fi
.PP
Generate a new certificate:
.PP
.nf
.RS
sudo pop3d -g
.RE
.fi
.PP
Test with OpenSSL:
.PP
.nf
.RS
openssl s_client -connect localhost:995 -quiet
.RE
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR pop3d.conf (5),
.BR pam (8),
.BR openssl (1),
.BR smtpd (8)
.SH AUTHORS
Originally written by Sunil Nimmagadda.
Production version adapted for Linux with PAM authentication.
.SH SECURITY
Always use SSL/TLS in production by setting
.B allow_plaintext = 0
in the configuration file.
Monitor logs for authentication failures and consider using fail2ban.
